My 5:15 AM view, and nope, I don't live on the tracks)  
Second session today was a skill focused two-piece workout. A) AMRAP 20 of 2 RMU and 6 dumbbell OHS (30kg/70lbs) B) 3 RFQ of 15 alt. dumbbell snatch (30kg/70lbs) with switch in the ground.  The A-piece would've been conditioning work if RMU's weren't such a skill/strength bottleneck and the OHS had been a bit lighter. I managed 12 rounds+2 RMU (26 RMU and 72 OHS) while only pushing my rest times in the last 5 minutes. Obviously still a glaring weakness, but I made some good technique improvements. I found a much tighter spot to hit in my kip that made the turnover much faster.  @stronghealthfitness

TGIFÔ∏è Tasted the "rebrew" of Carlsberg 1883 - the new release of a dark lager from... Yes, 1883. There is an interesting video on UT presenting the story and the process in recreating this beer from its original recipe with use of the original yeast. The story starts with the discovery of 134 years old beers in the cellars of @carlsberg @carlsbergdanmark in Valby, Denmark. At Impact Roasters, we believe that it is important to invest in job creation projects for the youth that resides in the areas where our coffee comes from. One of the projects that we have carried out through our nonprofit organization called Coffeeprint4Change is a concrete block production facility that employs local young men and women committed to being part of our aim to change and shape the local community. The training has already taken place, and now Coffeeprint4Change plans to develop other projects such as building schools, sanitation, facilities, libraries and other constructions that are needed to impact the whole community positively.

Valby station replaced the first station (1847-1864) in 1911. From 1934 also for s-trains. A temporary station served until 1941. The station was enlarged 1953 to the west and is in the top 10 of Denmarks most used stations

J. C. Jacobsen (1811-1887) Founder of world famous Carlsberg Breweries, named after his son, Carl and the hill (bjerg or berg) near the then small village Valby. Like the editors of Politivennen, Jacobsen was captain of the Copenhagen civil militsia, Borgerv√¶bningen, and minded for the bourgeois society. His relations to his son Carl (1842-1914), founder of Ny Carlsberg, 1871 deteriorated over the years, They never reconciled. @carlsberg @carlsbergbyen

Goodmorning everyone!  Ever heard of camu camu? Most people haven't, but actually this little cherry sized berry grows in the Amazon region in South America and is known to be rich in C-vitamin and in some cases has been measured to have 60-times more than a regular orange! Quite fascinating  The taste could remind us of acidic fruits like lime or lemon.  Here @cafeonthe6 we will be serving a new type of smoothie the next week, where we will include 100 grams of frozen camu camu pulp blended with a little water and 100 grams of mango pulp. Now that phase 1 of our remodel is coming to a close, we have the pleasure of putting up art pieces and making this house more of a home. A precious heirloom from my Grandma Weesie now hangs in the entryway- each woman represents the clothing worn from different Danish islands and regions. Reading about each area and the people that come from there fills my heart with an indescribable feeling of love, respect, and honor to be another link in the chain of that rich Danish blood. I am so grateful for my ancestors and the beautiful, artistic, humble example of one of the most influential people in my life, my "maga".

This week's commute - through Carlsberg.  Carlsberg City District is a small area in Vesterbro in Copenhagen, bordering to the Frederiksberg and Valby districts. The area is named after Carlsberg's beer, which was brewed on the premises from 1847 - 2008. However the visitor centre Visit Carlsberg and Jacobsen House Brewery, which produces special brews, are still located here.  The Carlsberg grounds are currently being transformed into a new neighbourhood called Carlsberg City District and is welcoming new tennants like educational instiutions, shops, caf√©s and its very own S-train station: Carlsberg Station. 
More Carlsberg - probably the oldest arse-grabbing in town... (pic. 3)  Carlsberg City District is a small area in Vesterbro in Copenhagen, bordering to the Frederiksberg and Valby districts. The area is named after Carlsberg's beer, which was brewed on the premises from 1847 - 2008. However the visitor centre Visit Carlsberg and Jacobsen House Brewery, which produces special brews, are still located here.  The Carlsberg grounds are currently being transformed into a new, but historic, neighbourhood called Carlsberg City District and is welcoming new tennants like educational instiutions, shops, caf√©s and its very own S-train station: Carlsberg Station.

Nordic Hamstring Ô∏èHaseskader er en skade der ofte foreg√•r i sportsgrene med h√∏j fart, enten i en sprint eller ved et strakt ben. Netop fordi haseskader ofte skader i yderbanen, er Nordic Hamstring √∏velsen en af de store skadesreducerende √∏velser for hasemuskulaturen da den tr√¶ner muskulaturen eksentriske kraft. ---------------------------------------------------Blandt andet har et dansk studie blandt 942 fodboldspillere vist at √∏velsen reducerede haseskader med 70%, og 85% hos dem der tidligere havde haft en hase skade. Det er enorme resultater.  Forslag til protokoller  van der Horst N, et al. Am J Sports Med. 2015. Ô∏èWeek 1, frequence 2, sets 2, reps per set 5 Ô∏èWeek 2, frequence 2, sets 2, reps per set 6 Ô∏èWeek 3, frequence 2, sets 3, reps per set 6 Ô∏èWeek 4, frequence 2, sets 3, reps per set 6-7-8 Ô∏èWeek 5, frequence 2, sets 3, reps per set 8-9-10  Petersen J, et al. Am J Sports Med. 2011. Hotel & Restaurant Fy & Bi, Valby. Halloween is an ancient celtic tradition (Samhain) to celebrate witches, ghosts and the dark powers. Christianity (catholicism) tried to it take over, and called it Allehelgensaften, All Saints Evening. Protestants disliked catholic traditions, so in 1770, it was abolished. But since 2000 the celtic tradition has been transformed and returned from the USA, and orange pumpkins with lights inside can be seen everywhere. Mwa ha hah!

Happy  At Impact Roasters, we take part in the campaign and would like to share our story about the journey we take to create the impact in the coffee world. Pilestykket, Husvildebarakker,  1947. 72 barracks, designed by architect Frederik Christian Lund (1896-1984). Functionalism. They were made in Sweden, still painted ‚ÄúSwedish Red‚Äù, and made for German refugees from refugee camp Kl√∏vermarkslejren. When they returned to Germany, the barracks were used for homeless. It was meant as a temporary solution, but later facilities were added and they still exist for permanent use. The lampposts in the background is the stadion Valby Idr√¶tspark. Christmas Basket - Ethiopian Coffee Body Scrub --------------------------------- The body scrub was developed by Impact Roasters team, and its inspiration stems from our aspiration for a more sustainable way of living.  The coffee grounds used as a base for the body scrub is a waste product, and we decided to put it to good use.  With a base of almond oil, coconut sugar, cinnamon and scented with peppermint essential oil the body scrub is to exfoliate, moisturize and antioxidize your skin.  The Ethiopian coffee body scrub is part of our Christmas Basket, but it can also be purchased separately at our roastery and coffee shop at Langgade st. . . . . .

Trekroner Bryggeri. The factory was established 1899, and was meant to house the brewery from 1899, designed by Caspar Leuning Borch. Only one third of the brewery is left. A war broke out between Carlsberg and De forenede Bryggerier, the latter swallowing up the brewery even before it moved in. The last beer left the factory in 1915, and was used by the tannery Ballin & Hertz. The building was modyfied for that purpose 1919-20 by architect Niels Hauberg. 30 years ago it was meant to be torn down, but luckily saved by unions and now used by the childrens‚Äô organization B√∏rns Vilk√•r.

‚ÄúSpinderiet‚Äù, Valby. The cotton factory (left) was build 1907 and closed by the end of the 1950s. It had its own nursery, Spindeg√•rden 1948-1965. Typical textile industry building with many and large windows to bring light inside. Then local crafters and industries moved in, until a shopping center was designed with old and new buildings 2007. Unlike many other shopping centers, is partly outdoor with a glass roof. Legendary union boss (SiD), Hardy Hansen (b. 1933) worked here for a short time until 1954.

Valby Station, early morning. This is where most of my hikes start - and end. The station is the second (1911), the first existed 1847-1864. Tracks for international, national, local and metropolitan lines, the latter shown on the photo, from 1934. In 1950-1953 the station expanded. Do I need to mention that the architect was Heinrich Wenck, my honoured followers? Tonite is showdown for 2017. Happy New Year! I wish you the very best in 2018, see you there.

Jesuskirken (1891, the separate tower, 1895). There are many photos of this church, this angle is scarcely used because it is only possible on a clear winter‚Äôs days. Designed by Vilhelm Dahlerup, financed by brewer Jacobsen, and inspired by ancient Italian cathedrals. The church got quite a few unusual decorations, like pentagrams, Zodiac symbols, and unlike most Danish churches, it is directed north-south (usually east-west).  @CopenhagenHeat
